The advertisement call of the new species, composed of 8–14 notes each with 4–18 pulses, and duration of 290–420 ms further differentiates it from
Scinax blairi
(single multi-pulsed note, 140–160 ms, 18–22 pulses;
Fouquette & Pyburn 1972
),
S. boesemani
(single multi-pulsed note, eight pulses;
Lescure & Marty 2000
),
S. chiquitanus
(single multi-pulsed note, 80–100 ms;
Duellman & Wiens 1993
),
S. cruentommus
(single multi-pulsed note, 350–370 ms;
Duellman 1972
),
S. danae
(single multi-pulsed note, 200–220 ms;
Duellman 1986
),
S. elaeochrous
(single multi-pulsed note, 170 ms;
